<div1 type="letter">
<pb facs="wfc.css00398.01"/>
<note type="letterhead">
Col. W. F. Cody. Proprietor<lb/>
F. H. Garlow, Manager<lb/>
Buffalo Bill's Hotel in the Rockies<lb/>
<figure n="photograph"></figure>
The Irma<lb/>
Cody, Wyoming,<lb/>
</note>


<opener>
<dateline>Feb. 10, 1914.</dateline>
<address>
<addrLine>Mr. John H. Tait,</addrLine>
<addrLine>Denver, Colo.</addrLine>
</address>
<salute>My dear Tait:</salute>
</opener>


<p>I got into a blizzard coming down from the TE. The car that was to meet me was broken down on the way and I drove half of the distance in one on those light buggies that we have at the TE, and I never was in such a blizzard in all my life. It was simply awful. I almost froze to death. I was chilled and it was a wonder I ever <unclear reason="torn">stood</unclear> the trip.</p>

<p>I am getting better, however, but I am still here on my back. I wouldn't say anything to the newspapers about it, that I am ill, but however, such is the case.</p>

<p>As soon as I am able to travel I am going to Chicago. Perhaps your next letter to me had better be addressed to the LaSalle Hotel.</p>

<p>I received your two letters and also the assay report on the mines. These last two strikes ought to add very much value to our mines down in Arizona.</p>

<p>I am not feeling strong enough and I have got so many things to write, so remember me to Bert and all the rest.</p>

<closer>
<salute>As ever,</salute>

<signed>Governor,<lb/>
T.</signed>

</closer>
</div1>

